## Designed-As-Intended Precheck

Designed-As-Intended Precheck:
- Missing protection: <<missing_protection|<guard / modifier / check name>|name the exact protection the bug-report claims should exist>>
- Canonical-design citation: <<canonical_citation|<spec / upstream / sibling-fn file:line>|cite the source that establishes the protection IS the intended design - protocol whitepaper, EIP, upstream reference implementation, sibling function in the SAME codebase that DOES have the protection, or a public post-mortem that mandated the protection>>
- Sibling-function comparison (where applicable): <<sibling_fn_comparison|<fn_A has guard at file:line; fn_B (contested) does NOT>|for asymmetric path-pair bugs (claim/finalize, sender/receiver, deposit/withdraw, mint/burn, propose/execute), tabulate which sibling DOES have the protection and which doesn't>>
- Team-acknowledgement scan: <<team_ack_scan|<grep result>|grep PRs/commits/discussions for prior team acknowledgement that the protection is intentional - e.g. "## Acknowledgement Scan" turns up SP-2961 or post-#77043 fix-commit confirming the team intended the guard>>
- Intentional-omission rebuttal pre-empt: <<intentional_omission_rebuttal|<source-backed rebuttal>|pre-empt the "this is working as intended" triager rebuttal: cite the source that PROVES the omission is not intentional (e.g. comment in source code says "TODO: add guard here", commit message references fixing the gap on a sibling path)>>
- Verdict: <<r45_verdict|omission-is-a-bug-not-by-design|omission-is-a-bug-not-by-design | by-design-walk-back | ambiguous-needs-team-disclosure>>

